"{\n  \"text\": \"Hi, Scotty here. I use the term living foods a lot, and I want to make a video talking about what the hell I mean by that. With a living food, I mean specifically food that has its bacterial profile intact still. And there's a lot of ways of disrupting that. Most of our food has had that disrupted through dehydration processing. A lot of different center of the supermarket type foods have been sterilized in this way where the existing bacteria has been taken out and then put into a sterile environment where it will stay sterile until it gets to you this way, it's safe. This is a dead food. And what's going wrong with us is that we don't have enough of the living foods, the prokaryotes that are attached to everything need to be attached to our food to some degree as well. And so what I mean by living foods are raw fruits, raw vegetables, and specifically fermented foods in terms of preservation. There's also some oil-based preservations and other anaerobic preservations. There's lots of good preservations that occur because of uh the refrigerator. But what I mean is things that haven't been processed in such a way that the bacterial content has been destroyed to make it safe. And that means cooking. That means acid preservations, that means uh taking the moisture out of them and all sorts of other ways that we commonly preserve our foods. There's nothing wrong with this, those are good calories. It's just that they are dead calories. They're not giving us the bacterial content that our gut needs. And eating enough of these foods over a long enough period of time is going to lead to your bacteria and your gut getting disassociated from the world that it needs to interact with. Anyway, thanks, y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hi, Scotty here.\",\n      \"start\": 0.8,\n      \"end\": 2.08,\n      \"duration\": 1.28,\n      \"confidence\": 0.985,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" Hi\",\n          \"start\":